(42, 17, 34, 61, 2, 9, 9, 'the one shall be taken, and the other shall be left', 'Judgment and Deliverance Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the distinction between the godly and the unjust. Luke highlights the separation of individuals at the time of judgment, while 2 Peter speaks to the Lord''s ability to deliver the godly and reserve the unjust for punishment.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 34, 39, 3, 16, 18, 'the one shall be taken, and the other shall be left', 'Judgment and Separation Theme', 'Both passages emphasize a distinction between individuals based on their relationship with God. In Luke, one is taken while the other is left, paralleling Malachi''s discernment between the righteous and the wicked.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 34, 52, 4, 16, 17, 'the one shall be taken', 'Connection of Being Taken', 'Both passages emphasize the idea of individuals being taken or left behind at a significant moment. Luke 17:34 mentions one man being taken, while 1 Thessalonians 4:17 describes believers being caught up to meet the Lord.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 34, 41, 13, 23, 23, NULL, 'Warnings of Future Events', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of being vigilant and aware of future events. Luke 17:34 speaks of individuals being taken or left, while Mark 13:23 warns to heed the foretelling of all things.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 34, 42, 13, 24, 24, NULL, 'Striving and Being Taken', 'Both passages emphasize the urgency of readiness for divine judgment. In Luke 17:34, the distinction between those taken and left reflects the necessity of striving to enter through the narrow gate in Luke 13:24.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 34, 19, 26, 9, 9, 'the one shall be taken', 'Connection of Judgment and Separation', 'This connection highlights the theme of separation between the righteous and the wicked. In Luke 17:34, one is taken while the other is left, paralleling the plea in Psalms 26:9 to not be gathered with sinners.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 35, 40, 24, 41, 41, 'the one shall be taken, and the other left', 'Parallel Grinding Women', 'Both passages emphasize two women grinding together, with one taken and the other left. This parallel highlights a similar scenario of separation during a moment of daily activity.', 'parallel', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 35, 2, 11, 5, 5, NULL, 'Connection of Grinding and Death', 'Both passages emphasize the act of grinding, linking the mundane task of women grinding together in Luke with the maidservant behind the mill in Exodus. This connection highlights the suddenness of divine judgment, as one is taken and the other left, paralleling the death of the firstborn in Egypt.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 35, 7, 16, 21, 21, 'grinding together', 'Grinding and Being Taken', 'Both passages emphasize the act of grinding, with Luke mentioning women grinding together and Judges depicting a man grinding in prison. This connection highlights the contrasting fates of those engaged in the same activity, one being taken and the other left.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 37, 40, 24, 28, 28, NULL, 'Connection of Eagles and Carcase', 'Both passages emphasize the gathering of eagles around a body or carcase, suggesting a similar imagery of judgment or end times. This connection highlights the consistent use of the metaphor across the texts.', 'parallel', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 37, 18, 39, 29, 30, NULL, 'Eagles and Prey Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the gathering of eagles around the slain. Luke 17:37 mentions eagles gathering where the body is, while Job 39:30 describes eagles seeking prey where the slain are. This connection highlights a thematic parallel of eagles associated with death and the pursuit of prey.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 37, 66, 19, 17, 18, 'wheresoever the body is', 'Gathering of Birds', 'Both passages emphasize the gathering of birds in relation to judgment. In Luke, eagles gather where the body is, while in Revelation, fowls are called to feast on the slain. This connection highlights a theme of divine judgment and the aftermath.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 37, 38, 13, 8, 9, 'thither will the eagles be gathered together', 'Gathering of the Faithful', 'This connection highlights the theme of separation and refinement in both passages. In Luke, the gathering of eagles suggests a selection process, while Zechariah speaks of a remnant being refined and saved.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 37, 30, 9, 1, 4, 'wheresoever the body is', 'Judgment and Divine Search', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine judgment and the inescapability of God''s presence. Both passages emphasize that no matter where one tries to hide, God''s reach extends everywhere, whether it be ''wheresoever the body is'' or ''though they dig into hell.''', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 37, 38, 14, 2, 2, 'gathered together', 'Gathering of Nations and Eagles', 'This connection highlights the theme of gathering, as both passages depict a gathering of entitiesâ€”eagles in Luke and nations in Zechariah. The imagery of gathering suggests a significant event or judgment occurring in both contexts.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 37, 27, 9, 26, 27, NULL, 'Desolation and Gathering Themes', 'This connection highlights the theme of desolation and gathering. In Luke, the gathering of eagles signifies a coming judgment, while in Daniel, the desolation of the city and sanctuary indicates a similar impending destruction.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 18, 1, 51, 4, 2, 2, 'ought always to pray', 'Connection of Prayer and Persistence', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of prayer and perseverance. Luke encourages not to faint in prayer, while Colossians urges to continue in prayer with vigilance.', 'theme', 0.9649999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 18, 1, 45, 12, 12, 12, NULL, 'Connection of Prayer and Persistence', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of prayer in the life of believers. Luke encourages not to faint in prayer, while Romans stresses continuing instant in prayer, highlighting the necessity of perseverance in communication with God.', 'theme', 0.867, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 18, 1, 52, 5, 17, 17, 'always to pray', 'Connection of Prayer Persistence', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of continual prayer. Luke 18:1 encourages believers to ''always pray,'' while 1 Thessalonians 5:17 instructs to ''pray without ceasing.'' This connection highlights a shared theme of unwavering commitment to prayer.', 'theme', 0.825, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 18, 1, 50, 4, 6, 6, 'pray, and not to faint', 'Connection of Prayer and Persistence', 'This connection highlights the importance of prayer in both passages. Luke emphasizes the need to ''pray, and not to faint,'' while Philippians encourages believers to present their requests ''by prayer and supplication.''', 'theme', 0.734, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 18, 1, 49, 6, 18, 18, 'always to pray', 'Connection of Prayer and Perseverance', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of persistent prayer. Luke encourages believers to ''always pray,'' while Ephesians calls for ''praying always'' with perseverance. This connection highlights a shared theme of unwavering commitment to prayer.', 'theme', 0.727, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 18, 1, 19, 55, 16, 17, 'men ought always to pray', 'Connection of Prayer and Persistence', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of prayer, with Luke urging believers to ''always pray'' and Psalms expressing a commitment to pray ''evening, and morning, and at noon.'' This connection highlights the necessity of persistent communication with God.', 'theme', 0.6779999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 18, 1, 24, 29, 12, 12, NULL, 'Connection of Prayer and Persistence', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of prayer. Luke encourages continual prayer without losing heart, while Jeremiah assures that God will listen when called upon in prayer.', 'theme', 0.629, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 18, 2, 20, 29, 7, 7, NULL, 'Connection of Righteousness and Wickedness', 'This connection highlights the contrast between the judge who ''feared not God, neither regarded man'' and the righteous who ''considereth the cause of the poor.'' Both passages emphasize the moral responsibility of individuals towards others, particularly the vulnerable.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 18, 2, 19, 8, 1, 4, 'feared not God', 'Judgment and Human Worth', 'This connection highlights the contrast between the judge who ''feared not God'' and the psalmist''s reflection on ''what is man, that thou art mindful of him?''. Both passages emphasize the nature of authority and the value of humanity in the face of indifference or neglect.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 18, 2, 42, 18, 4, 4, 'which feared not God, neither regarded man', 'Judge''s Attitude Toward God', 'This connection highlights the judge''s self-awareness of his lack of fear for God and regard for man. Both passages emphasize his character as someone who does not hold reverence for divine or human authority.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 18, 2, 24, 22, 16, 17, 'feared not God, neither regarded man', 'Judgment and Moral Responsibility', 'This connection highlights the contrast between a judge who does not fear God or regard man and the expectation of righteous judgment for the poor and needy. Both passages emphasize the moral responsibility of judges to act justly, with Jeremiah condemning those who prioritize covetousness and violence.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 18, 2, 26, 22, 6, 8, 'feared not God, neither regarded man', 'Judgment and Oppression Themes', 'Both passages emphasize a lack of regard for justice and the vulnerable. The judge in Luke, who ''feared not God, neither regarded man,'' parallels the oppressive actions of Israel''s leaders in Ezekiel, who ''dealt by oppression with the stranger'' and ''vexed the fatherless and the widow.''', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 18, 2, 33, 3, 1, 3, 'feared not God, neither regarded man', 'Judgment and Corruption in Leadership', 'Both passages emphasize the failure of leaders to uphold justice. The judge in Luke is characterized by a lack of regard for God and man, paralleling the corrupt leaders in Micah who hate good and love evil.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 18, 2, 2, 18, 21, 22, 'feared not God', 'Judges and Their Character', 'This connection highlights the contrasting character of judges. Luke describes a judge who ''feared not God,'' while Exodus emphasizes the need for judges who ''fear God'' and are truthful.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
